review_text: For only 120 tablets for $15, it's a total rip-off. Sorry to say. I will continue using the ones I use. It takes more than 1 tablet for me and that is not unusual. As we get older our bodies stop making melatonin, so that is why most people require supplemental melatonin. For me, I require at least 50 mg or higher. That may sound like a lot, but I'm a health buff and I've been doing research for years regarding all-things-healthy for the body. There are studies done (actual clinical studies, not just people's opinion) that have shown that some people can take up to 100 mg without any side effects whatsoever. I know this is true for me, because there are some nights I just can't sleep due to the chronic pain I live with. I also make sure not to have any blue light devices (i.e. smart phones, lap tops, "smart" anything, etc.), and even light from alarm clocks can disrupt one's sleep. So, you know your own body. If you don't need more than 1 tablet, consider yourself fortunate, because it can get expensive. Fortunately, I've found the very few brands I use in tandem with one another. They are good brands, high quality melatonin and they give you 300 to 400 tablets per bottle/bag and are very cost effective.

review_text: This works great to improve my formerly fragmented sleep, whereas even 10 or 12gm doses have no noticeable sleep benefit for me. In addition, unlike it's herbal competitors: valerian root and 5-HTP, melatonin has potent anti-cancer, anti-inflammatory, and anti-oxidant properties, which I consider worthwhile at this low price, aside from any improvement in sleeping. Formal studies have failed to find a mean sleep benefit of melatonin supplements for non-seniors. However, most people take a dose less than 10gm. Maybe, like me, some of them need a bigger dose to feel a benefit. Actually, later, I discovered that 15mg is optimal for me, as 20mg is really a bit too strong, causing grogginess the whole next day. Seniors, like me, generally produce much less melatonin at night than the younger crowd, hence are much more likely to benefit from melatonin supplements, in terms of their sleep. Non-seniors with sleep or anxiety problems are probably better off trying one of the OTC GABA agonists, such as GABA, valerian root, or my recommendations: either theanine or skullcap(or baicalin). In addition to sleep-promoting and anti-anxiety action, like melatonin, these latter two have long-term possible benefits of potent anti-cancer, anti-inflammatory, and anti-oxidant activity. If you tend to act out your bad dreams, like I do, by moving your arms and legs around, kicking, and such, that's abnormal, and predisposes you to eventual Parkinson's! Melatonin supplement is the preferred 'medicine' to keep that under control. That's yet another reason for me to keep taking it!
review_header: Take it for its potent anti-cancer, anti-inflammatory, anti-oxidant, and pro-sleep properties.

review_text: I wanted to give this product a full chance, so I took it for almost two weeks as directed. It's supposed to melt "under the tongue" which it eventually does, but it takes a LOT of time. Unfortunately my experience with this has been a total disappointment. On paper, it's supposed to be 4 times as powerful as the melatonin I'd been used to taking (5mg). The problem is that after almost 2 weeks of trying, these tablets have had zero effect on my sleep - not any at all, that I observed. In the past, 5mg tablets seem to make me sleepy after about an hour or so, these never gave me that effect, even after the tablets (eventually) dissolved under the tongue. I would have thought that it would have had MORE of an effect, but there has been literally none at all. I caved in and bought a bottle of 5mg tablets at a local store to replace these. The only saving grace is that the flavor of these isn't unpleasant... but in my experience, there was literally zero, none, absolutely no other effect whatsoever, with these tablets.

review_text: Super happy with this stuff! Just got it yesterday day as I was about to have a tough time sleeping, like usual, and I took one and slept like a medicated baby. So I just swallowed it cause a bunch of reviews says it tastes bad...medication always does. Let me say that I am in my late 30's and have been dealing with a panic disorder and extreme insomnia since I was 11yrs old. For several years now I've been seeing a psychiatrist and am medicated to the point where the medication gives me control over my life to live normally, which is awesome but I still have to wake and function like everyone else, so the medication stops short at keeping me asleep for longer than 5-6 hours, which is okay but I really want more like 7-8 but that would require heavy meds that would be hard to wake from. So all that being said. I am no expert, nor am I giving any medical advice...but I always thought melatonin was a joke, it turns out that's because I was taking like 1-3 mg and hoping for sleep. 20 mgs is a game changer and really worked for me, at least last night I slept for exactly 8hrs and 34mins ( I timed it just to see). I feel great not groggy at all! I'm sure this needs to only be taken every now and then, as to not build a tolerance, so it shouldn't be heavily relied on. But this stuff is great and so far really worked for me. These pills are not scored but easily can be cut with a pill cutter regardless as they are not super dense. Happy sleeping everyone

review_text: When I went to open the first bottle, I noticed there was flimsy film around the cap, and no further safety features (ie: a seal over the interior bottle opening). I was able to just unscrew the cap with the seal still on it, there was no interior seal, so I could just pull out the cotton and have access to the product. This concerned me, so I tried the same thing with the second bottle and that one was just as vulnerable. The bottles came in a plastic bag, with flimsy plastic wrappings around part of the neck of the bottle which could easily be screwed off/tampered with. I did not use the product as I am concerned about the lack of safety. It was too late to return it, so this review is to warn others not to buy this product until proper safety features are in place.
